Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides a small nursery with everything itself at such facilities: colour walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the sons of Arch.Design's employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose study came out of numerous known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its miniguard.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Designs to your workers in the framework of their social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with child care.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a provision of over 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding is running out (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the miniguardy running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the request for funding contributed to the Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day long. The day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day care is provided for children without age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a mini-guardian, it can only simultaneously accommodate up to five children, even though with shifts more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
While it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-guardian programme are comparable to the regular pre-school education programme.
In it, children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach up to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive as they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is located among the Sink companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this programme reinforced the marketing of staff.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch Gaudí interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remember the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with oneiric lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, there is a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twist of forms continues to surprise us also inside it.
Corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the balconies, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
La Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, came from the remodeling of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial man Josep Batlló, initially insisted on bringing down the previous building and starting from zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design it by Antoni Gaudí alone.
In the design he collaborated with the architect Josep María Jujol.
In fact, in their plans of the project there were ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Milá House and the Gaudi Güell Park, in which other parts of it are found.
Due to its organic shape, the locals soon after their finalization nicknamed her "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows began to call it "the house of the woods".
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious reasons.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the building rules at all and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although clearly the data on the expected reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so impacted by the result it requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public arena.
On the contrary, the arrangements were never made; only fifteen days after the town hall application, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented into a jewelry shop.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the hall doors and a larger group can thus communicate without any problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of the accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very profitable business and extended the visits to the common area and to the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches the 16,50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other constructions of Gaudí in the city.
