More and more parents use monitoring devices to control their children
Fear for children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle monitoring, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in the event of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment, the device has the approximate size of a cell box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people feared the case of the missing Anička and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We're all trying to tell ourselves that it's not about spying, but about another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the providers of follow-up devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they get in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," says Pilin.
In your opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in case of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even younger children show great creativity when intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid control of them."
"Before, the parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bočková says.
In his view, it is questionable whether in the event of an attack such a device is really useful.
"If it is a ready kidnapping, the author will practically always check whether the child carries any type of electronic device that can reveal its location."
"Now's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is being extended, it will also look for them, since their sale will certainly be made with a lot of publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack of a pedophil.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which provides follow-up services for both vehicles and individuals, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can be helpful.
"The device can be configured to regularly send the position after a given period."
"If you suffer damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices incorporate a tilt meter, so if the person simply turns out and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
