For a long time, there have been six major elements that are essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you think as much as possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
As Anbar said, finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbio discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "shows itself is that in other planetary environments, there may be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, at Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the replacement of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who conducted the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so it speculated that a microbes exposed to both could replace one another.
"Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"So it can be complicated for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is different enough so it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, by some means, it calls biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
Researchers collected bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
Microbial grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic in its place raises the possibility that there can naturally exist a form of life that uses arsenic, whether in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an Assistant Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic may be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found proving it works.
The arsenic was more common in the early Earth eras, he said, so researchers speculated that the first ways of life could have used it.
"If it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not only the way life was formed on Earth in the past," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Institutes.
