Can the civic hold a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, this week a bit of civilism has been unleashed in Washington.
Is it an ominous predation of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and Congress leaders did not make any progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as they all say, it was at least a short discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to rule, rather than being another empty episode to gain partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the chairman's deficit commission was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months has generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a period of testing, examining each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent evaluations by the participants was made was with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and deeply rooted as to suggest any rapid change in the climate that existed over the past two years.
Whether it is tax, expenditure, health care or social aid, the two sides are in the opposite poles.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to how to say things," said Pete Wehner, an official of Bush's administration now in the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections wake up partisan passions, which then fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, in particular those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax reductions are overdue at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to extend unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot believe that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying the unemployment allowance for the unemployed.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, together with the ratification of the new START Nuclear Disarmament Pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation in the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to a continuous bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
On the contrary, he stated that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement begins.
"After the things that have to be done are carried out, in the short term, psychology will revert the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civilism can lead to genuine cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a trial for the major event in 2012," he said.
The reasons have a great deal to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to their creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their promises to cut the state's expenses and nullify the new health law.
These support lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and the retirement age, and the reduction of expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have carried out one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected on the panel, suggesting that there are at least few bases or desires for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of positive shocks, when the Republicans challenge Obama's budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they're losing will probably change course and look for compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
partisanism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans of Congress than between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendent choice in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common points on issues that still divide them.
