EU changes rules to get visas
People should attend Visa Request Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure to process a visa at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will be changed.
Under the new procedure, most applicants should attend Visa Applicant Service (ASC) centres before their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff shall take biometric information from the applicant, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer need to make a payment to make the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the messaging service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
People wishing to renew their visas will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only come to the nearest AUC where they will present their documents and take their marks.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken at the AUC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain at this time less than in the past.
Also, those applying for visas in Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolets/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
