A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday, the United Nations has proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GEI) in a quantity corresponding to almost one third of the additional decrease to be carried out to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is framed in the broad range of concrete projects that the United Nations expects to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70 per cent of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by bulbs of electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1,800 million tons (Gt) of GEI emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen, last year, large issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this quantity should still be reduced to stabilize by 2020 the increase in temperatures by two degrees centigrade to prevent it from being out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy spending is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced by twice as much.
The fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in one hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit very little heat.
Above all, they contain nothing of mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers make instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluocompact bulbs, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that melts with the incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power stations whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
