In the past, the press tried to understand what was in secret in the embassies.
Currently, it is embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s caps on its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to consider whether the fast-blocked funding promises (called fast-start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French chaps have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has committed to contribute EUR 7.200 million in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has placed its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was a remarkable result and was appreciated for what really was worth: the developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 EUR 2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of EUR 7.200 million in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure a complementary effort, without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what means "new and additional".
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has made reference to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years in terms of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the costs of previous years or the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the sharing of donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider each euro to be equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is obvious to present a euro that is going to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan to the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent to a interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find this reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it for its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union brings a euro to fulfill its commitment, France only gives ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start funding, France commits double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending just €36.1 million, you can give the impression that you spend 420 million "new and additional", as you promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems to be Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can just lend?) as in the negotiations, since developing countries are not foolish...
The early financing chapter is a short-term detail in relation to the whole climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra sand grain in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move forward discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast start of France and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
